EBOLA: FALSE ALARM IN FLIGHT
============================
Date: Fri 4 Apr 1997
From: Jack Woodall <woodall@wadsworth.org>

The object of posting the correspondence that follows is NOT to point the
finger at any one country, airport or airline, because it could have
happened to any of them. The
object is to point out the need for countries and airlines to establish --
rapidly -- procedures for handling a suspected case of Ebola, or other
transmissible disease emergency, in flight and on the ground.
It is necessary to arrange for, among other things:
- care of the patient on board while reducing the possibility of transmission
- rapid transfer procedures to a designated infectious disease hospital
onthe ground
- procedures for isolating and feeding passengers held on the ground, and
giving them facilities to communicate with their relatives.
After the Ebola case last year that was flown from Gabon to South Africa on
a regular scheduled flight, and the case of resistant TB who infected
passengers on another flight just last month, it is not a question any more
of whether those procedures will ever be needed -- they are needed NOW.
We would be happy to hear from any airport, airline or public health
authority about procedures now being implemented.
[Refs: Ebola - South Africa (08): nurse died 961124232731
TB (resistant) spread on plane - Africa/Europe/USA 970324164625]
--
Jack Woodall, Ph.D., Director, ProMED-mail
Wadsworth Center
New York State Dept.of Health, Albany NY, USA
e-mail: woodall@wadsworth.org
