Source: the OUTBREAK page: http://www.outbreak.org/
>> In Reply to OUTBREAK's Inquiry Regarding the Suspected Ebola Case
>> in Perth. 2/28, 1997
>> Ebola: False Alarm in Australia
>>
>> ----------------------------------------------------------------------
>>
>> In Reply to The Qantas plane was not refused permission to land but
>> OUTBREAK's returned to Perth after takeoff with a medical
>> Inquiry emergency. This information was all the passengers were
>> Regarding told. There was NO panic on the plane and the patient
>> the was removed from the plane and sent to hospital. Once
>> Suspected the patient had been assessed as not having an illness
>> Ebola Case consistent with Viral haemorrhagic fever no further
>> in Perth. action was taken. The plane was then allowed to depart
>> 2/28, 1997 for Sydney which is 4 hours flying time away.
>>
>> The underlying medical condition is a matter of
>> confidentiality between the patient and her physician,
>> however I can categorically confirm that there was not
>> a public health risk.
>>
>> This was a false alarm which was handled competently
>> and efficiently by all the agencies involved and has
>> provided a valuable learning experience.
>>
>> I don't believe there is a need for any further
>> correspondence on this matter which is now closed.
>>
>> Lewis Marshall
>> Medical Coordinator
>> Communicable Disease Control
>> Health Department of Western Australia
>>
>> ----------------------------------------------------------------------
>> Ebola: False On Friday, February 21 at 2:00 a.m., local radio in
>> Alarm in Melbourne reported a problem at Sydney Airport. A
>> Australia Qantas flight from South Africa was not given landing
>> permission because of a suspected case of Ebola
>> infection on board.
>>
>> A female passenger began bleeding from the nose and
>> ears, and other passengers panicked and began to yell
>> "Ebola!"
>>
>> The flight was diverted to Perth, in western
>> Australia, where ambulances, police and fire
>> department were waiting, and the plane was
>> quarantined. Australian television showed the woman
>> being taken to the hospital.
>>
>> Australian medical authorities have declared that the
>> passenger did not have Ebola, and both local media and
>> e-mail sent to OUTBREAK confirm that it was a false
>> alarm.
>>
>> It is not clear yet what caused the passenger's
>> bleeding. But a spokesman for the Department of
>> Transport and Regional Development has suggested that
>> the bleeding might have been due to a change in air
>> pressure.
>>
>> Sources: E-mail from Vail Riches (2/22-26) in
>> Melbourne; Rod Hart, Department of Transport and
>> Regional Development in Canberra, Australia (2/25);
>> and Des Devlin of Sydney Morning Herald (2/23).
>>
>> ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Date: Mon, 31 Mar 1997 00:26:00 -0800
From: <outbreak-admin@outbreak.org (Outbreak)>

Re: Ebola scare in Australia.
I was on that flight Harare to Sydney. The way they handled the emergency
was terrible, considering the number or people and the nature of the case.
[But] There was no panic. People were relatively calm about the whole
situation and there was no mention on board the plane of Ebola.
Medical staff were very slow to respond to the situation and were not
waiting for the plane when we touched down. We were all forced to wait and
watch this woman who was obviously in a lot of discomfort. It took approx.
45 minutes after touchdown before medical staff moved this woman off the
aircraft and the rest of the passengers were forced to wait and hope.
We were given nothing except peanuts and we hadn't eaten in hours. We were
then informed that we couldn't fly on to Sydney because of the curfew at
Sydney airport, and they left us sitting in the airport and then in the
terminal. We spent at least 9 hours in Perth and Qantas didn't even put us
up in a hotel. They eventually organised to get us some food, and they
finally gave us phonecards to call the people who we had organised to meet
us at Sydney airport.
The staff at Sydney airport were not available to inform waiting friends
and relatives of the difficulties we had encountered.
Staff handled the situation reasonably well in the beginning, however, I
would not like to be put through such a situation again.
[Name & address not provided - Mod.JW]
